After
divorcing second wife Ava Gardner in 1957, Sinatra snapped up the 
duplex, which occupies the 22nd and 23rd floors, and the space was 
transformed into a four-bedroom, six-bathroom apartment worthy of the 
Rat Pack.

Ol' Blue Eyes helped to design the riverside pad and construction was completed in 1961. Sinatra called it home until 1972.

While arguably the ultimate bachelor pad, Sinatra met, married and then divorced Mia Farrow while living there.

The jewel in the penthouse's crown was a glassed-in, rooftop party room
where guests would mingle under 18-foot ceilings and enjoy sweeping 
views of the East River.

